nodes.name: Health Information Technology for Economic and Clinical Health Act
nodes.description: U.S. legislation to promote the adoption and meaningful use of health information technology.

nodes.authority: U.S. Department of Health and Human Services (HHS)
nodes.parent_framework: HIPAA (Health Insurance Portability and Accountability Act)
nodes.name: Health Information Technology for Economic and Clinical Health Act
nodes.description: Federal law strengthening HIPAA enforcement expanding breach notification requirements extending compliance to business associates and providing incentives for EHR adoption.

nodes.name: Improved Health Information Technology
nodes.description: Subtitles covering enhanced privacy and security provisions testing of health information technology grants and loans funding and enforcement mechanisms.

nodes.name: Medicare and Medicaid HIT
nodes.description: Medicare and Medicaid incentives for meaningful use of certified EHR technology and EHR adoption for eligible healthcare providers.

nodes.name: Improved Privacy and Security Provisions
nodes.description: Enhanced HIPAA privacy and security protections extended business associate liability tiered penalties breach notification requirements and expanded enforcement authority.

nodes.name: Testing of Health Information Technology
nodes.description: EHR certification standards testing procedures for certified systems and ONC authority to certify electronic health record technology.

nodes.name: Grants and Loans Funding
nodes.description: Financial resources for EHR adoption workforce training funding and health IT infrastructure support to promote electronic health record adoption.

nodes.name: Privacy and Security Provisions (Enforcement)
nodes.description: Enforcement mechanisms tiered civil monetary penalties enhanced OCR authority business associate direct liability breach notification requirements and safe harbor provisions.

nodes.name: Improved Privacy and Security Provisions
nodes.description: Enhanced HIPAA privacy and security protections extended business associate liability tiered penalties breach notification requirements and expanded enforcement authority.
nodes.key_concepts: Extended business associate compliance; Direct liability for violations; Enhanced privacy protections; Security Rule enhancements; Breach notification rights

nodes.name: Testing of Health Information Technology
nodes.description: EHR certification standards testing procedures for certified systems and ONC authority to certify electronic health record technology.
nodes.key_concepts: EHR certification standards; Testing procedures; ONC certification authority; Certified EHR technology requirements; Functional requirements

nodes.name: Grants and Loans Funding
nodes.description: Financial resources for EHR adoption workforce training funding and health IT infrastructure support to promote electronic health record adoption.
nodes.key_concepts: EHR adoption grants and loans; Workforce training funding; Health IT infrastructure support; Financial incentives for technology; Provider support programs

nodes.name: Privacy and Security Provisions (Enforcement)
nodes.description: Enforcement mechanisms tiered civil monetary penalties enhanced OCR authority business associate direct liability breach notification requirements and safe harbor provisions.
nodes.key_concepts: Tiered penalty framework (4 tiers); Enhanced OCR enforcement authority; Business associate direct liability; Breach notification requirements; Safe Harbor Amendment (2021) provisions; Criminal liability

nodes.heading: Definitions
nodes.description: Definitions related to HITECH privacy provisions and key terms
nodes.content_summary: Defines critical terms including unsecured PHI breach compromise presumption low risk of compromise business associate direct liability and related enforcement concepts used throughout HITECH Act
nodes.key_concepts: Unsecured PHI, Breach definition, Compromise presumption, Low risk threshold, Business associate, Subcontractor, Direct liability, Electronic PHI

nodes.heading: Breach Notification
nodes.description: Notification in case of breach of unsecured protected health information
nodes.content_summary: Comprehensive breach notification requirements establishing mandatory notification of individuals within 60 calendar days discovery of breach of unsecured PHI includes individual media and HHS notification procedures timeline and content requirements
nodes.key_concepts: Breach discovery, 60-day timeline, Individual notification, Media notification (500+), HHS notification, Unsecured PHI, Risk assessment, Four-factor test, Compromise presumption, Safe harbor provisions

nodes.heading: Notification by Business Associates
nodes.description: Requirements for business associates to notify covered entities of breaches
nodes.content_summary: Business associates must notify covered entities of any breach of unsecured PHI without unreasonable delay and no later than 60 calendar days from discovery of breach included detailed breach information for covered entity to issue individual notifications
nodes.key_concepts: Business associate notification, Covered entity notification, 60-day timeline, Detailed breach information, Affected individuals list, PHI categories, Mitigation steps, Investigation results

nodes.heading: Business Associate Agreements
nodes.description: Requirements for business associate agreements and compliance
nodes.content_summary: HITECH requires covered entities to ensure business associates and all subcontractors comply with HIPAA Privacy and Security Rules establishes direct liability for business associates and requires written business associate agreements with specified terms and conditions
nodes.key_concepts: Business Associate Agreement, Direct liability, Subcontractor liability, BAA requirements, Compliance obligations, Minimum necessary, Uses and disclosures, Safeguard implementation, Breach reporting, Termination clauses

nodes.heading: Civil Monetary Penalties
nodes.description: Tiered civil monetary penalties for HIPAA violations
nodes.content_summary: HITECH established four-tier penalty framework for HIPAA violations scaled to culpability level Tier 1 unknowing violations $100-50000 per violation Tier 2 reasonable cause $1000-50000 Tier 3 willful neglect corrected $10000-50000 Tier 4 willful neglect not corrected $20000-50000 with $1.5M annual cap
nodes.key_concepts: Tier 1 unknowing violation, Tier 2 reasonable cause, Tier 3 willful neglect (corrected), Tier 4 willful neglect (not corrected), Penalty ranges, Annual caps, Mitigating factors, Corrective action plans, Penalty assessment

nodes.heading: Enforcement Activities of Secretary
nodes.description: HHS enforcement authority and procedures for HIPAA compliance
nodes.content_summary: OCR enforcement authority to investigate HIPAA complaints conduct periodic compliance audits issue penalties issue warning letters require corrective action plans audit both covered entities and business associates with same enforcement procedures and authority expanded from original HIPAA
nodes.key_concepts: OCR investigation authority, Compliance audits, Desk audits, On-site audits, Penalty authority, Corrective action plans, Warning letters, Notice of violation, Evidence collection, Subpoena authority

nodes.heading: Business Associate Requirements
nodes.description: Specific requirements for business associates regarding safeguards and breach notification
nodes.content_summary: Business associates must implement HIPAA Privacy and Security Rule safeguards conduct regular risk assessments maintain audit logs provide breach notification to covered entities and maintain documentation of compliance efforts business associates directly liable for HIPAA violations and subject to same penalties as covered entities
nodes.key_concepts: Business associate safeguards, Risk assessment requirement, Audit logging, Breach notification, Direct liability, Same penalties as covered entities, Compliance documentation, Security measures implementation, Training requirements

nodes.heading: Criminal Penalties
nodes.description: Criminal penalties for knowing HIPAA violations
nodes.content_summary: HITECH establishes criminal liability for knowing HIPAA violations obtaining or disclosing PHI under false pretenses with commercial advantage or private gain criminal penalties up to $250000 fine and or 10 years imprisonment for single knowing violation multiple years imprisonment for multiple violations
nodes.key_concepts: Knowing violation, Commercial advantage, Private gain, Criminal penalties, $250,000 fine, 10-year imprisonment, Multiple offenses, False pretenses, Department of Justice referral

nodes.heading: Accounting of Disclosures
nodes.description: Enhanced accounting of disclosures requirements
nodes.content_summary: HITECH expands accounting of disclosures requirement to 3 years for covered entities and business associates must track all uses and disclosures of PHI provide detailed accounting including date recipient purpose and type of information individual can request accounting at any time covered entity must provide within 30 days
nodes.key_concepts: 3-year accounting history, All disclosures tracked, Detailed accounting content, Recipient identification, Purpose of disclosure, PHI type disclosed, Accounting request procedure, 30-day response timeline

nodes.heading: Restrictions on Use and Disclosure
nodes.description: Requirements for restricting uses and disclosures of PHI
nodes.content_summary: Individuals have enhanced right to request restrictions on use and disclosure of PHI covered entity must implement appropriate restrictions business associate must comply with use and disclosure restrictions contained in business associate agreement applies minimum necessary standard to all uses and disclosures
nodes.key_concepts: Use restrictions, Disclosure restrictions, Individual requests, Restriction implementation, Minimum necessary standard, Business associate compliance, Covered entity obligations

nodes.heading: Certified EHR Technology
nodes.description: Requirements for certified electronic health record technology
nodes.content_summary: Office of National Coordinator establishes standards for certifying EHR systems certified EHR must meet functional security and privacy requirements establish testing procedures and maintain authoritative list of certified systems EHR vendors must develop systems meeting certification standards and undergo certification testing
nodes.key_concepts: ONC certification standards, EHR functional requirements, Security requirements, Privacy requirements, Testing procedures, Certified system list, Vendor certification, Compliance testing, Interoperability requirements

nodes.heading: Grants for Health Information Technology
nodes.description: Grants and financial resources for healthcare providers to adopt EHR systems and support health IT implementation and workforce development
nodes.content_summary: HHS and CMS provide grants to eligible healthcare providers and organizations for EHR adoption implementation and training grants support acquisition implementation workforce training and infrastructure development to accelerate health IT adoption across healthcare
nodes.authority: HHS and Centers for Medicare & Medicaid Services (CMS)
nodes.key_concepts: Eligibility criteria, Grant amounts, Application procedures, Eligible uses, Workforce training, Infrastructure development, Grant accountability, Clawback provisions

nodes.heading: Loans for Health Information Technology
nodes.description: Loan programs for healthcare organizations to finance EHR adoption and implementation costs and related health IT infrastructure development
nodes.content_summary: HHS and CMS establish loan programs for eligible healthcare providers with favorable terms to finance EHR and health IT implementation loans support technology acquisition system integration and infrastructure development to reduce capital barriers to EHR adoption
nodes.authority: HHS and Centers for Medicare & Medicaid Services (CMS)
nodes.key_concepts: Loan eligibility, Interest rates, Repayment terms, Loan amounts, Collateral requirements, Default procedures, Loan guarantees, Disbursement procedures

nodes.heading: Workforce Development for Health Information Technology
nodes.description: Funding for workforce development training and education programs for healthcare IT professionals and clinical staff to support EHR adoption and health IT implementation
nodes.content_summary: CMS and HHS support development and delivery of training curricula for health IT professionals clinical informatics training clinical staff training and organizational change management training to develop qualified workforce to support EHR systems development testing implementation and operations
nodes.authority: HHS and Centers for Medicare & Medicaid Services (CMS)
nodes.key_concepts: Training program development, Curriculum design, Clinical informatics training, EHR system training, Change management training, End-user training, Certification programs, Continuing education, Academic partnerships

nodes.heading: Enforcement Actions and Corrective Actions
nodes.description: Requirements for corrective action plans and enforcement procedures when HIPAA violations are identified
nodes.content_summary: OCR requires covered entities and business associates to develop and implement corrective action plans to remediate identified violations corrective action plans must include root cause analysis remediation steps implementation timeline responsible parties and success metrics OCR monitors implementation and verifies compliance
nodes.key_concepts: Corrective action plans, Root cause analysis, Remediation procedures, Timeline requirements, Implementation monitoring, Compliance verification, Success metrics, CAP modifications

nodes.heading: Privacy and Security Rules Enhancements
nodes.description: Enhancements to HIPAA Privacy and Security Rules through HITECH
nodes.content_summary: HITECH enhances HIPAA Privacy Rule with expanded individual rights mandatory breach notification extended accounting requirements and strengthened restrictions on use and disclosure HITECH enhances Security Rule with mandatory risk assessment requirements encryption standards access control requirements audit logging requirements and incident response requirements
nodes.key_concepts: Risk assessment (mandatory), Encryption standards, Access controls, Audit logging, Incident response, Individual rights, Breach notification, Minimum necessary standard, Privacy training

nodes.heading: Safe Harbor Amendment Recognized Security Practices
nodes.description: Penalty mitigation for organizations implementing recognized security practices as of January 5 2021 amendment
nodes.content_summary: OCR may reduce or waive penalties for Tier 3 willful neglect violations if entity demonstrated implementation of recognized security practices from NIST Cybersecurity Framework or HHS 45 CFR 164.308(a)(7) guidance for 12 months prior to breach violation recognized practices include encryption standards access controls audit logging key management risk assessment incident response
nodes.key_concepts: Recognized security practices, NIST CSF compliance, HHS 405(d) guidance, Implementation period (12+ months), Penalty reduction/waiver, Encryption (AES-256, TLS 1.2+), MFA requirements, Audit logging (6+ years)

nodes.heading: State Attorney General Authority
nodes.description: State-level enforcement authority under HIPAA and HITECH for consumer protection and health information privacy violations
nodes.content_summary: State attorneys general have authority to pursue civil actions for HIPAA and HITECH violations affecting state residents state AGs can recover actual damages statutory damages up to $100 per violation court costs and attorney fees state AGs also have authority to pursue public health and consumer protection actions for information privacy breaches
nodes.key_concepts: Civil action authority, State resident jurisdiction, Actual damages, Statutory damages, Court costs, Attorney fees, Public health authority, Consumer protection, Coordination with federal enforcement

nodes.heading: EHR Testing and Certification Standards
nodes.description: ONC testing and certification standards for electronic health record systems and health IT modules
nodes.content_summary: ONC establishes comprehensive testing and certification standards for EHR systems and health IT modules testing procedures validate compliance with functional requirements security standards privacy standards and interoperability requirements certified EHR systems must meet these standards to qualify for meaningful use incentive payments and federal procurement
nodes.key_concepts: Testing standards, Functional requirements, Security testing, Privacy testing, Interoperability testing, Certification criteria, Certified system list, Annual recertification, Version updates, Module certification

nodes.heading: EHR Incentive Payments Meaningful Use
nodes.description: Medicare and Medicaid incentive payments for eligible providers adopting certified EHR technology and achieving meaningful use objectives
nodes.content_summary: CMS administers EHR incentive programs providing Medicare and Medicaid payments to eligible providers hospitals and critical access hospitals for adopting certified EHR systems and demonstrating meaningful use of EHR technology meaningful use requires demonstrating clinical objectives administrative objectives and interoperability objectives to qualify for incentive payments payments decrease after 2015 and phase out transitioning to promoting interoperability program and MIPS framework
nodes.key_concepts: Eligibility criteria, Incentive payment amounts, Meaningful use objectives, Clinical objectives, Administrative objectives, Interoperability objectives, Attestation requirements, Payment schedules, Transition to MIPS

nodes.heading: Coordinated Enforcement Procedures
nodes.description: Coordinated enforcement procedures between HHS OCR and State Attorneys General for HIPAA and HITECH violations
nodes.content_summary: HHS OCR and state attorneys general coordinate enforcement efforts to avoid duplication and ensure consistent enforcement of HIPAA and HITECH requirements OCR handles federal enforcement and penalty assessment state AGs pursue state-level civil actions through coordination agreement entities may be subject to both federal and state enforcement actions for significant violations
nodes.authority: HHS Office for Civil Rights (OCR) and State Attorneys General
nodes.key_concepts: Coordination procedures, Federal enforcement, State enforcement, Dual enforcement, Settlement coordination, Information sharing, Mutual recognition of settlements

nodes.heading: Subcontractor Accountability
nodes.description: Direct HIPAA liability of subcontractors engaged by business associates and healthcare organizations
nodes.content_summary: HITECH extends direct HIPAA liability to all subcontractors and downstream vendors engaged by business associates subcontractors must be subject to HIPAA Privacy and Security Rules and have contractual agreements flowing down compliance obligations business associates remain responsible for monitoring subcontractor compliance with HIPAA requirements
nodes.key_concepts: Subcontractor definition, Direct liability, Written agreements required, Flow-down requirements, Compliance obligations, Monitoring requirements, Breach notification (60-day), Enforcement authority

nodes.heading: Mitigating Factors in Penalty Assessment
nodes.description: Factors OCR considers when determining HIPAA violation penalties and penalty amounts
nodes.content_summary: OCR considers multiple mitigating factors when assessing civil monetary penalties including good faith compliance efforts nature and extent of violation degree of culpability organizational size prior violation history implementation of recognized security practices prompt correction upon discovery cooperation with OCR investigation financial hardship and duration of violation these factors may result in penalty reduction within assessed tier ranges
nodes.key_concepts: Good faith efforts, Violation nature, Culpability degree, Organization size, Prior violations, Security practices, Prompt correction, OCR cooperation, Financial hardship, Violation duration

nodes.heading: Definitions - Unsecured PHI Definition
nodes.description: Organizations must understand and apply statutory definition of unsecured PHI in all compliance activities
nodes.key_controls: Documentation of definitions; Training materials; Policy statements

nodes.heading: Definitions - Breach Definition
nodes.description: Organizations must consistently apply statutory definition of breach requiring notification
nodes.key_controls: Breach definition in policies; Assessment procedures; Decision documentation

nodes.heading: Definitions - Compromise Presumption
nodes.description: Organizations must understand compromise presumption requirement that breaches compromise PHI unless proven otherwise
nodes.key_controls: Risk assessment process; Mitigation measures documentation

nodes.heading: Definitions - Business Associate Liability
nodes.description: Organizations must recognize that business associates are directly liable for HIPAA violations with same penalties as covered entities
nodes.key_controls: BAA language; Compliance monitoring procedures

nodes.heading: Breach Notification - Individual Notification
nodes.description: Covered entities must notify affected individuals of breaches of unsecured PHI without unreasonable delay no later than 60 calendar days
nodes.key_controls: Notification templates; Contact procedures; Delivery tracking

nodes.heading: Breach Notification - Media Notification
nodes.description: Covered entities must notify prominent media outlets if breach affects 500 or more residents in same state or jurisdiction within 60 calendar days
nodes.verification_method: Media notification records; Press release documentation
nodes.key_controls: Media contact lists; Press release templates; Delivery tracking

nodes.heading: Breach Notification - HHS Notification
nodes.description: Covered entities must notify HHS without unreasonable delay and no later than 60 calendar days for breaches affecting 500+ individuals or annually for smaller breaches
nodes.key_controls: HHS reporting form; Submission procedures; Tracking logs

nodes.heading: Breach Notification - Content Requirements
nodes.description: Breach notifications must include breach description dates affected individuals categories of PHI involved recommended individual steps entity investigation steps and contact information
nodes.key_controls: Notification templates; Content checklist; Quality review

nodes.heading: Breach Notification - Timeliness
nodes.description: Notification must occur without unreasonable delay but in all cases within 60 calendar days of discovery of breach
nodes.key_controls: Breach discovery log; Timeline tracking; Compliance monitoring

nodes.heading: Business Associate Breach Notification
nodes.description: Business associates must notify covered entities of any breach of unsecured PHI without unreasonable delay no later than 60 calendar days from discovery
nodes.verification_method: Breach notification letter; Delivery confirmation; Affected individual list
nodes.key_controls: BA notification procedures; Contact lists; Escalation procedures

nodes.heading: Business Associate Breach Detail Requirement
nodes.description: Business associates must provide detailed breach information including affected individuals PHI types mitigation steps and investigation results to enable covered entity notification
nodes.verification_method: Breach detail documentation; Information completeness review
nodes.key_controls: BA breach form; Information checklists; Documentation requirements

nodes.heading: Business Associate Agreement Requirement
nodes.description: Covered entities must execute written Business Associate Agreements with all entities that create receive maintain or transmit PHI on their behalf
nodes.key_controls: BAA template; Execution tracking; Version control

nodes.heading: Business Associate Agreement - Permitted Uses and Disclosures
nodes.description: Business Associate Agreements must specify exactly which uses and disclosures of PHI are permitted and for what purposes
nodes.key_controls: BAA permitted uses clauses; Scope definition; Change procedures

nodes.heading: Business Associate Agreement - Safeguard Requirements
nodes.description: Business Associate Agreements must require business associates to implement HIPAA Security Rule safeguards and Privacy Rule restrictions
nodes.key_controls: Safeguard requirements clauses; Compliance verification; Audit procedures

nodes.heading: Business Associate Agreement - Breach Notification
nodes.description: Business Associate Agreements must require business associates to notify covered entities of breaches within 60 calendar days
nodes.key_controls: Breach notification clauses; Contact procedures; Escalation paths

nodes.heading: Business Associate Agreement - Subcontractor Management
nodes.description: Business Associate Agreements must require management of subcontractors with same HIPAA and HITECH compliance obligations through written agreements
nodes.key_controls: Subcontractor management clauses; Flow-down templates; Monitoring procedures

nodes.heading: Penalty - Tier 1 Unknowing Violation
nodes.description: Penalties for unknowing violations range from $100 to $50000 per violation with annual cap of $1.5 million
nodes.key_controls: Corrective action plan; Compliance evidence; Risk mitigation

nodes.heading: Penalty - Tier 2 Reasonable Cause Violation
nodes.description: Penalties for reasonable cause violations range from $1000 to $50000 per violation with annual cap of $1.5 million
nodes.key_controls: Corrective action plan required; Compliance evidence

nodes.heading: Penalty - Tier 3 Willful Neglect (Corrected)
nodes.description: Penalties for willful neglect violations corrected within 30 days range from $10000 to $50000 per violation minimum $100000 annually with cap of $1.5 million
nodes.key_controls: Corrective action plan; Prompt correction evidence

nodes.heading: Penalty - Tier 4 Willful Neglect (Not Corrected)
nodes.description: Penalties for willful neglect violations not corrected within 30 days range from $20000 to $50000 per violation minimum and maximum $100000 to $1.5 million annually
nodes.key_controls: Mandatory corrective action; Compliance evidence required

nodes.heading: Penalty Mitigation - Recognized Security Practices
nodes.description: Penalties for Tier 3 violations may be reduced or waived if entity demonstrated implementation of recognized security practices for 12+ months preceding breach violation (Safe Harbor Amendment 2021)
nodes.verification_method: Documentation of recognized practices; Security audit records
nodes.key_controls: NIST CSF compliance; Encryption standards; Access controls; MFA; Audit logging

nodes.heading: OCR Authority - Investigation
nodes.description: HHS OCR has authority to investigate HIPAA and HITECH violations including responding to complaints and issuing subpoenas
nodes.key_controls: Complaint intake process; Investigation procedures; Documentation standards

nodes.heading: OCR Authority - Audits
nodes.description: HHS OCR has authority to conduct periodic compliance audits both desk audits and on-site audits of covered entities and business associates
nodes.key_controls: Audit procedures; Record retention; Audit cooperation

nodes.heading: OCR Authority - Penalty Assessment
nodes.description: HHS OCR has authority to assess civil monetary penalties for HIPAA and HITECH violations following investigation
nodes.key_controls: Penalty calculation; Payment procedures

nodes.heading: Business Associate - Safeguards Implementation
nodes.description: Business associates must implement HIPAA Privacy Rule and Security Rule safeguards as required by covered entity agreements
nodes.key_controls: Safeguard inventory; Implementation procedures; Audit trails

nodes.heading: Business Associate - Risk Assessment
nodes.description: Business associates must conduct regular risk assessments of PHI security vulnerabilities and implement remediation measures
nodes.key_controls: Risk assessment methodology; Vulnerability scanning; Remediation procedures

nodes.heading: Business Associate - Audit Logging
nodes.description: Business associates must maintain comprehensive audit logs of all PHI access and changes with retention period of at least 6 years
nodes.verification_method: Audit log records; Log retention verification
nodes.key_controls: Log retention policies; Access logging; Change tracking

nodes.heading: Business Associate - Breach Notification
nodes.description: Business associates must notify covered entities of breaches of unsecured PHI within 60 calendar days including affected individuals data involved and mitigation steps
nodes.key_controls: Breach notification procedures; Contact protocols; Escalation procedures

nodes.heading: Criminal Liability - Knowing Violation
nodes.description: Individuals who knowingly obtain or disclose PHI under false pretenses face criminal penalties up to $250000 fine and or 10 years imprisonment
nodes.key_controls: Legal compliance; Training; Access controls; Audit monitoring

nodes.heading: Criminal Liability - Commercial Advantage
nodes.description: Criminal liability applies to those who knowingly obtain or disclose PHI with intent to obtain commercial advantage or private gain
nodes.key_controls: Access control; Monitoring; Investigation procedures

nodes.heading: Accounting of Disclosures - 3-Year History
nodes.description: Covered entities and business associates must maintain detailed accounting of all PHI disclosures for 3-year period upon request
nodes.key_controls: Disclosure tracking system; Record retention; Audit logging

nodes.heading: Accounting of Disclosures - Content
nodes.description: Accounting must include date of disclosure recipient of PHI purpose of disclosure type of PHI disclosed and description of information
nodes.key_controls: Accounting templates; Content standards; Quality procedures

nodes.heading: Accounting of Disclosures - Timeliness
nodes.description: Covered entities must provide accounting of disclosures within 30 calendar days of individual request
nodes.verification_method: Disclosure records with timestamps; Response tracking
nodes.key_controls: Request intake; Timeline tracking; Compliance monitoring

nodes.heading: Restrictions on Use and Disclosure - Individual Request
nodes.description: Individuals have right to request restrictions on use and disclosure of PHI for any purpose including treatment payment and operations
nodes.key_controls: Request intake process; Documentation standards; Communication procedures

nodes.heading: Restrictions on Use and Disclosure - Implementation
nodes.description: Covered entities must implement restrictions requested by individuals and ensure restrictions are applied and maintained
nodes.key_controls: Restriction tracking system; Notification procedures; Compliance monitoring

nodes.heading: Corrective Action Plan - Development
nodes.description: Upon identification of violations covered entities and business associates must develop corrective action plans including root cause analysis remediation steps and implementation timelines
nodes.verification_method: CAP documentation; Root cause analysis; Implementation tracking
nodes.key_controls: CAP templates; Analysis procedures; Tracking procedures

nodes.heading: Corrective Action Plan - Implementation
nodes.description: Corrective action plans must be implemented with OCR monitoring and verification of compliance with specified timelines and success metrics
nodes.verification_method: Implementation records; Progress tracking; Completion verification
nodes.key_controls: Progress tracking; Monitoring procedures; Completion procedures

nodes.heading: Privacy and Security Rules - Risk Assessment
nodes.description: Covered entities and business associates must conduct regular risk assessments of ePHI storage transmission and systems identifying vulnerabilities and threats
nodes.key_controls: Risk assessment methodology; Vulnerability analysis; Remediation procedures

nodes.heading: Privacy and Security Rules - Encryption
nodes.description: Covered entities and business associates must encrypt electronic PHI at rest using AES-256 or equivalent and in transit using TLS 1.2 or higher
nodes.key_controls: Encryption standards documentation; Technical implementation; Audit procedures

nodes.heading: Privacy and Security Rules - Access Controls
nodes.description: Covered entities and business associates must implement strong access controls including unique user identification multi-factor authentication role-based access control and session timeouts
nodes.key_controls: User ID policy; MFA procedures; RBAC configuration; Timeout settings

nodes.heading: Privacy and Security Rules - Audit Logging
nodes.description: Covered entities and business associates must maintain comprehensive audit logs of all PHI access and system changes with retention of at least 6 years
nodes.verification_method: Audit log records; Log retention verification
nodes.key_controls: Log retention policy; Tamper detection; Access tracking

nodes.heading: Safe Harbor - Recognized Security Practices
nodes.description: Entities implementing recognized security practices from NIST Cybersecurity Framework or HHS 45 CFR 164.308(a)(7) guidance for 12+ months preceding breach may receive penalty reduction or waiver for Tier 3 violations
nodes.verification_method: Documentation of practices; Security audit records; Training records
nodes.key_controls: NIST CSF compliance; Implementation documentation; Audit trails

nodes.heading: State Attorney General - Civil Action Authority
nodes.description: State attorneys general have authority to pursue civil actions against entities for HIPAA and HITECH violations affecting state residents
nodes.key_controls: Legal compliance; Cooperation with state AG

nodes.heading: State Attorney General - Damages Recovery
nodes.description: State AGs can recover actual damages statutory damages up to $100 per violation court costs and attorney fees for HIPAA and HITECH violations
nodes.key_controls: Settlement procedures; Documentation

nodes.heading: Subcontractor - Direct Liability
nodes.description: Subcontractors and downstream vendors are directly liable under HIPAA for violations with same penalties as covered entities and business associates
nodes.key_controls: Written agreements; Compliance terms; Verification procedures

nodes.heading: Subcontractor - Written Agreement
nodes.description: Covered entities and business associates must execute written agreements with all subcontractors flowing down HIPAA and HITECH compliance obligations
nodes.key_controls: Agreement templates; Flow-down language; Tracking procedures

nodes.heading: Subcontractor - Breach Notification
nodes.description: Subcontractors must notify business associates and covered entities of breaches of unsecured PHI within 60 calendar days with affected individual details
nodes.key_controls: Breach notification procedures; Contact lists; Escalation paths

nodes.heading: Mitigating Factors - Good Faith Effort
nodes.description: OCR may reduce penalties if entity demonstrates good faith effort to comply with HIPAA and HITECH requirements
nodes.key_controls: Compliance documentation; Training records; Policy implementation

nodes.heading: Mitigating Factors - Prior Violations
nodes.description: OCR considers prior violation history when assessing penalties with fewer prior violations generally resulting in lower penalties
nodes.key_controls: Compliance history; Improvement documentation

nodes.heading: Mitigating Factors - Recognized Security Practices
nodes.description: OCR considers implementation of recognized security practices when assessing penalties which may result in reduction or waiver particularly for Tier 3 violations
nodes.key_controls: NIST CSF compliance; Security audit results; Implementation evidence

nodes.heading: Certified EHR - Functional Requirements
nodes.description: Certified EHR systems must include patient medical record management electronic prescribing drug interaction checking lab result viewing secure messaging audit logs and access controls
nodes.verification_method: Certification documentation; Feature testing; Compliance verification
nodes.key_controls: Functional testing; System documentation; Feature verification

nodes.heading: Certified EHR - Security Standards
nodes.description: Certified EHR systems must meet ONC security standards including encryption access control audit logging and incident response capabilities
nodes.verification_method: Security testing; Certification records; Audit trails
nodes.key_controls: Security testing procedures; Compliance verification; Audit documentation

nodes.heading: Certified EHR - Interoperability
nodes.description: Certified EHR systems must support health information exchange through APIs and standards-based data exchange
nodes.verification_method: Interoperability testing; Data exchange verification; API documentation
nodes.key_controls: Interoperability testing; API compliance; Data standards

nodes.heading: EHR Testing - ONC Certification Testing
nodes.description: Vendors must submit EHR systems to ONC-designated testing bodies for certification testing validating compliance with functional security and privacy requirements
nodes.verification_method: Certification testing results; ONC approval; Compliance documentation
nodes.key_controls: Testing procedures; Documentation; Compliance evidence

nodes.heading: EHR Testing - Certification Maintenance
nodes.description: EHR vendors must maintain certification of systems ensuring ongoing compliance with standards and undergoing recertification annually or when systems are updated
nodes.verification_method: Certification records; Update documentation; Recertification completion
nodes.key_controls: Recertification procedures; Version tracking; Compliance monitoring

nodes.heading: EHR Incentives - Eligible Provider
nodes.description: Eligible providers must adopt ONC-certified EHR systems and demonstrate meaningful use to qualify for Medicare and Medicaid incentive payments
nodes.verification_method: Attestation submission; Meaningful use documentation; Payment records
nodes.key_controls: Meaningful use tracking; Objective achievement; Attestation procedures

nodes.heading: EHR Incentives - Meaningful Use Objectives
nodes.description: Providers must achieve clinical administrative and interoperability objectives to demonstrate meaningful use of certified EHR systems
nodes.verification_method: Objective achievement records; Data validation; Attestation documentation
nodes.key_controls: Objective tracking; Data collection; Reporting procedures

nodes.heading: EHR Incentives - Incentive Payments
nodes.description: Providers demonstrating meaningful use receive Medicare and Medicaid payments on sliding scale with payments decreasing over time and transitioning to MIPS framework
nodes.verification_method: Payment records; Attestation submissions; Compliance documentation
nodes.key_controls: Payment tracking; Attestation procedures; Compliance documentation

nodes.heading: Grants - Eligibility
nodes.description: HHS and CMS provide grants to eligible healthcare organizations and providers for EHR adoption implementation and workforce training
nodes.verification_method: Grant application; Eligibility verification; Award documentation
nodes.key_controls: Application procedures; Eligibility documentation; Award tracking

nodes.heading: Grants - Permitted Uses
nodes.description: Grant funds must be used for EHR acquisition implementation workforce training and health IT infrastructure development
nodes.verification_method: Budget documentation; Expenditure records; Audit results
nodes.key_controls: Budget allocation; Expense tracking; Audit procedures

nodes.heading: Loans - Loan Programs
nodes.description: HHS and CMS establish loan programs with favorable interest rates for healthcare providers to finance EHR technology acquisition and implementation
nodes.verification_method: Loan agreement; Disbursement records; Repayment schedule
nodes.key_controls: Loan procedures; Repayment tracking

nodes.heading: Loans - Favorable Terms
nodes.description: EHR loans offer favorable interest rates terms and schedules to reduce capital barriers to technology adoption
nodes.verification_method: Loan documentation; Interest calculations; Repayment records
nodes.key_controls: Loan term documentation; Payment procedures

nodes.heading: Workforce Training - Program Development
nodes.description: HHS and CMS fund development of health IT workforce training programs including clinical informatics EHR system training and organizational change management
nodes.verification_method: Training program documentation; Curriculum; Enrollment records
nodes.key_controls: Curriculum development; Training delivery; Participant tracking

nodes.heading: Workforce Training - Certification Programs
nodes.description: Training programs must include certification options for health IT professionals to develop qualified workforce
nodes.verification_method: Certification program documentation; Completion records; Credential verification
nodes.key_controls: Certification procedures; Credential tracking; Quality assurance

nodes.authority_source: HIPAA Title II; HITECH Act Title I
nodes.domains_covered: Breach Notification; Business Associate Oversight; Privacy Protections; Security Safeguards; Risk Assessment; Encryption; Access Controls; Audit Logging; Incident Response; EHR Adoption; Meaningful Use
nodes.primary_responsibilities: Implement HIPAA Privacy Security and Breach Notification Rules; establish policies and procedures for PHI protection; designate privacy and security officers; manage business associates; report breaches; maintain documentation of compliance
nodes.description: Health plans health care clearinghouses and certain health care providers as defined by HIPAA who directly transmit or use electronic health information in conducting business
nodes.compliance_obligations: Direct HIPAA compliance obligations for Privacy Rule Security Rule Breach Notification Rule and HITECH amendments; business associate oversight; individual rights fulfillment
nodes.examples: Hospitals; Health Systems; Physician Practices; Dental Offices; Mental Health Clinics; Insurance Companies; Health Plans
nodes.enforcement_authority: HHS OCR - direct penalty authority; State Attorneys General; Department of Justice (for criminal violations)

nodes.authority_source: HIPAA Title II; HITECH Act Subtitle A (Section 13405-13408)
nodes.domains_covered: Breach Notification; Business Associate Compliance; Safeguards Implementation; Risk Assessment; Audit Logging; Encryption; Access Controls; Incident Response; Subcontractor Accountability; Contractual Compliance
nodes.primary_responsibilities: Comply with HIPAA Privacy and Security Rules as specified in Business Associate Agreements; implement safeguards for ePHI protection; report breaches to covered entities within 60 days; maintain audit logs and records; ensure subcontractor compliance; provide evidence of compliance
nodes.description: Entity that performs functions or activities on behalf of a covered entity or provides services to a covered entity that involve creation receipt maintenance or transmission of electronic protected health information (ePHI)
nodes.compliance_obligations: Direct HIPAA compliance obligations same as covered entities; must execute Business Associate Agreements; subcontractor management; breach notification; specific safeguard implementation; audit and documentation requirements
nodes.examples: Cloud Service Providers; EHR Vendors; Billing Companies; IT Support Firms; Data Centers; Claims Processors; Revenue Cycle Vendors; Consultants; Attorneys; Auditors; Transcription Services
nodes.enforcement_authority: HHS OCR - direct penalty authority; State Attorneys General; Covered Entity (contractual); Subcontractors flow-down; Department of Justice (for criminal violations)

nodes.authority_source: HIPAA Title II; HITECH Act Subtitle A (Section 13423)
nodes.domains_covered: Breach Notification; Safeguards Implementation; Audit Logging; Encryption; Access Controls; Incident Response; Compliance Documentation; Subcontractor Accountability if they engage further vendors
nodes.primary_responsibilities: Comply with HIPAA Privacy and Security Rules as specified in subcontractor agreements; implement required safeguards for ePHI protection; report breaches to business associates within 60 days; maintain compliance with documented requirements; cooperate with audits
nodes.description: Entity engaged by a business associate to create receive maintain or transmit electronic protected health information (ePHI) on behalf of the covered entity or business associate; must comply with same HIPAA and HITECH requirements as business associates
nodes.compliance_obligations: Direct HIPAA liability same as covered entities and business associates; must execute written agreements with business associates; breach notification within 60 days; safeguard implementation; full compliance obligations
nodes.examples: API Developers; Data Backup Services; Hosting Providers; System Integrators; Consultants; Managed Service Providers; Authentication Services; Security Auditors
nodes.enforcement_authority: HHS OCR - direct penalty authority; Business Associate (contractual); Covered Entity (through flow-down); State Attorneys General; Department of Justice (for criminal violations)

nodes.authority_source: HIPAA Enforcement Rule (45 CFR Part 160); HITECH Act Title I Subtitle D
nodes.domains_covered: Enforcement & Penalties; Breach Notification Investigation; Business Associate Audit; Risk Assessment Verification; Safeguard Audit; Audit Logging Review; Access Control Audit; Encryption Standards; Incident Response Procedures; Corrective Action Plans; Penalty Assessment; Safe Harbor Evaluation
nodes.primary_responsibilities: Investigate HIPAA and HITECH violations from complaints or audits; conduct periodic compliance audits and examinations; assess penalties according to tiered structure; issue enforcement actions including warning letters notices of violation and corrective action plan requirements; provide guidance and technical assistance to entities; maintain list of breaches affecting 500+ individuals
nodes.regulatory_scope: Federal United States; authority over all states and territories
nodes.description: The Office for Civil Rights (OCR) within the U.S. Department of Health and Human Services responsible for enforcing HIPAA Privacy Rule Security Rule Breach Notification Rule and HITECH Act amendments against covered entities and business associates
nodes.compliance_obligations: Statutory authority to investigate and enforce; penalty assessment authority from $100 to $50000 per violation with $1.5M annual cap; authority to subpoena documents and issue subpoenas; audit authority over covered entities and business associates; ability to defer to State Attorneys General; issuing guidance documents and technical assistance
nodes.examples: HHS Office of General Counsel; Regional OCR Directors; OCR Investigators
nodes.enforcement_authority: Direct enforcement authority; coordinates with State Attorneys General; refers criminal violations to Department of Justice; coordination with other federal agencies including ONC and CMS

nodes.authority_source: HITECH Act Title I Subtitle B (Section 13412 13420)
nodes.domains_covered: EHR Certification Standards; EHR Testing Standards; Functional Requirements; Security Standards; Privacy Standards; Interoperability Standards; Data Exchange Standards; Certified Systems List Maintenance; Standards Evolution; Coordination with CMS
nodes.primary_responsibilities: Establish and maintain EHR certification standards and requirements; designate authorized testing bodies to conduct EHR system certification testing; maintain authoritative list of certified EHR systems; monitor and update certification standards; coordinate with CMS on Meaningful Use program; provide technical guidance on certified EHR requirements; maintain Office of Health Information Technology policy direction
nodes.description: Federal agency within HHS responsible for certifying electronic health record (EHR) systems and establishing EHR certification standards and testing procedures to promote health information exchange and meaningful use of certified systems
nodes.role_name: Office of the National Coordinator for Health Information Technology (ONC)
nodes.compliance_obligations: Authority to establish EHR certification standards; designate testing bodies; maintain certified systems list; update standards and requirements; coordinate with CMS on incentive programs and meaningful use; ONC authority applies to all EHR vendors and systems used in incentive programs
nodes.examples: EHR Vendors; Technology Developers; Testing Bodies; CMS - for incentive program alignment
nodes.enforcement_authority: Indirect through certification authority and standards setting; no direct penalty authority but works with CMS on incentive program enforcement; can decertify systems for non-compliance

nodes.authority_source: HITECH Act Title I Subtitle C (Section 13413 13414 13421) and successor legislation (MACRA)
nodes.domains_covered: EHR Incentive Programs; Meaningful Use Objectives; Payment Administration; Provider Eligibility; Attestation Requirements; Data Quality Standards; Interoperability Objectives; Payment Schedules; Program Oversight; Fund Recovery
nodes.primary_responsibilities: Administer EHR incentive payment programs for eligible Medicare and Medicaid providers; establish meaningful use objectives and measures; collect provider attestation for meaningful use achievement; make incentive payments to eligible providers demonstrating meaningful use; establish payment amounts and schedules; monitor provider compliance with meaningful use requirements; transition providers to new payment models; coordinate with ONC on certification standards and testing
nodes.description: Federal agency within HHS responsible for administering Medicare and Medicaid programs and managing EHR Incentive Payment programs including Meaningful Use and successor programs (Promoting Interoperability MIPS Alternative Payment Models)
nodes.compliance_obligations: Authority to administer incentive programs; set meaningful use objectives and payment amounts; determine provider eligibility; establish payment schedules; require attestation; monitor compliance with meaningful use requirements; authority over Medicare and Medicaid payment programs; ability to recover funds for non-compliance
nodes.examples: Medicare Providers; Medicaid Providers; Eligible Hospitals; Clinics; Critical Access Hospitals; ONC for standards coordination
nodes.enforcement_authority: Indirect through payment authority; can withhold or recover payments for non-compliance; coordinates with HHS OCR on privacy and security issues; works with ONC on EHR certification standards

nodes.authority_source: State law authority for health information privacy and civil enforcement; HIPAA Section 1176(b) which allows State AG enforcement; HITECH Act Section 17939 amendment
nodes.domains_covered: State-Level Enforcement; Civil Damages Recovery; Consumer Protection; Breach Notification Follow-up; Coordination with Federal Enforcement; State Resident Protection
nodes.primary_responsibilities: Investigate HIPAA and HITECH violations affecting state residents; pursue civil actions against entities for damages; recover actual damages and statutory damages for residents harmed by violations; coordinate with HHS OCR on federal enforcement; provide consumer protection related to health information privacy; enforce state privacy laws that may exceed HIPAA requirements
nodes.regulatory_scope: State jurisdiction with responsibility for state residents; can pursue damages for state residents injured by violations
nodes.description: State-level official responsible for protecting citizens and state residents from HIPAA and HITECH violations affecting them; has authority to pursue civil actions for violations of state law regarding privacy and health information security
nodes.compliance_obligations: Authority to pursue civil actions for HIPAA and HITECH violations affecting state residents; can recover actual damages statutory damages up to $100 per violation court costs and attorney fees; authority to pursue public health and consumer protection actions; can establish settlement agreements with entities
nodes.examples: Healthcare Entities Operating in State; Residents of State Injured by Violations
nodes.enforcement_authority: Direct civil enforcement authority; coordinates with HHS OCR on federal enforcement; can refer criminal matters to state and federal prosecutors; consumer protection authority

nodes.authority_source: HIPAA Section 1307 Criminal Penalties; HITECH Act Section 13410 Criminal Penalties Amendment
nodes.domains_covered: Criminal Liability Prosecution; Knowing Violations; False Pretenses; Commercial Advantage; Private Gain; Criminal Penalties; Imprisonment Authority; Fraud Investigation
nodes.primary_responsibilities: Prosecute criminal violations of HIPAA referred by HHS OCR or other agencies; represent federal government in criminal proceedings; pursue criminal penalties including fines and imprisonment; investigate criminal conduct related to PHI disclosure or obtaining PHI under false pretenses; coordinate with HHS OCR on criminal referrals
nodes.description: Federal agency responsible for prosecuting criminal violations of HIPAA and HITECH Act including knowing violations by individuals or entities that obtain or disclose PHI under false pretenses with intent for commercial advantage or private gain
nodes.compliance_obligations: Authority to prosecute criminal violations; pursue criminal penalties including fines up to $250000 and imprisonment up to 10 years; authority to bring criminal charges for knowing violations; coordinate with law enforcement agencies
nodes.examples: HHS OCR; FBI; Law Enforcement Agencies
nodes.enforcement_authority: Exclusive federal criminal prosecution authority; receives referrals from HHS OCR; initiates criminal investigations; coordinates with FBI and other federal law enforcement

nodes.authority_source: HIPAA Title II Privacy and Security Rules; HITECH Act Title I Subtitle B (EHR Certification) and Subtitle A (Safeguards); ONC Certification Standards
nodes.domains_covered: System Development Compliance; Security Standards; Encryption; Access Controls; Audit Logging; Breach Notification; EHR Certification; Interoperability Standards; Testing and Validation; Customer Support for Compliance
nodes.primary_responsibilities: Design and develop systems meeting HIPAA Security Rule requirements and ONC certification standards if seeking certified status; implement security controls encryption access controls audit logging; comply with HIPAA Breach Notification requirements if business associate; submit systems for ONC certification testing if seeking certified EHR designation; maintain compliance with evolving standards and requirements; support customer compliance efforts
nodes.regulatory_scope: Federal United States; applies to all developers selling systems used with PHI
nodes.description: Organization that develops designs or manufactures electronic health information systems health information exchange systems personal health record systems or health IT modules subject to HIPAA and HITECH requirements when handling PHI
nodes.compliance_obligations: If acting as business associate must comply with HIPAA Privacy and Security Rules and breach notification; if developing certified EHR must meet ONC standards and certification requirements; subject to HIPAA and HITECH enforcement if handling PHI or acting as BA
nodes.examples: EHR Vendors; PHR Developers; Health Information Exchange Organizations; Health IT Consultants; Software Development Companies; Cloud Providers
nodes.enforcement_authority: HHS OCR if acting as business associate; ONC if seeking EHR certification; State Attorneys General; Department of Justice for criminal violations; Covered Entities (contractual)

nodes.authority_source: HIPAA Privacy Rule (45 CFR Parts 164.500-164.528); HITECH Act Section 13410 Accounting of Disclosures; Section 13402 Breach Notification; 42 U.S.C. §1177(a)
nodes.domains_covered: Individual Rights; Breach Notification; Access to Records; Amendment Rights; Restriction Requests; Accounting Rights; Confidential Communication; Complaint Filing Authority; Damages Recovery in Civil Actions
nodes.primary_responsibilities: Exercise individual rights under HIPAA and HITECH including right to receive copy of medical records; right to request amendments; right to request restrictions on uses and disclosures; right to receive notification of breaches; right to request confidential communication; right to receive accounting of disclosures; right to file complaints with HHS OCR or State AGs for violations
nodes.regulatory_scope: Federal United States; applies to all U.S. healthcare records
nodes.description: Healthcare consumer or patient who is the subject of protected health information (PHI) and holds individual rights under HIPAA Privacy Rule and enhanced rights under HITECH Act including right to notification of breaches right to access and amend records and right to request restrictions on uses and disclosures
nodes.compliance_obligations: Right to access and amend PHI; right to notification of breaches of unsecured PHI within 60 days; right to detailed accounting of disclosures for 3 years; right to request restrictions; right to request confidential communication; right to complain to HHS OCR or State AGs for violations
nodes.examples: Healthcare Consumers; Patients; Research Subjects
nodes.enforcement_authority: Rights holder; can file complaints with HHS OCR or State AGs; can participate in civil litigation for damages; can assert rights in regulatory proceedings

nodes.authority_source: HIPAA Privacy Rule (45 CFR § 164.308(a)(2)); HITECH Act amendments requiring enhanced privacy protections
nodes.domains_covered: Privacy Policy Development; Privacy Training; Individual Rights Fulfillment; Breach Investigation; Minimum Necessary Assessment; Risk Assessment; Compliance Monitoring; Breach Notification Coordination
nodes.primary_responsibilities: Develop and implement privacy policies procedures and safeguards for PHI protection; ensure compliance with HIPAA Privacy Rule minimum necessary standard and use and disclosure restrictions; oversee individual rights fulfillment including access amendments and restriction requests; manage privacy training programs; respond to privacy complaints and breaches; coordinate with security officer; report to organization leadership on privacy compliance status
nodes.regulatory_scope: Organizational-wide scope within covered entity or business associate
nodes.description: Individual designated by covered entity or business associate responsible for developing implementing and maintaining privacy policies and procedures for handling PHI and ensuring compliance with HIPAA Privacy Rule and HITECH Act requirements
nodes.compliance_obligations: Responsibility for implementing and maintaining Privacy Rule compliance; oversight of PHI use and disclosure; individual rights management; documentation of privacy policies and procedures; breach notification coordination; training and awareness programs
nodes.examples: Covered Entities; Business Associates; Healthcare Providers
nodes.enforcement_authority: Reports to organization leadership; subject to HHS OCR audit and enforcement authority; accountable for privacy compliance failures

nodes.authority_source: HIPAA Security Rule (45 CFR Parts 164.308-164.320); HITECH Act Subtitle A Section 13417 Security Enhancements; Section 13418 Safe Harbor Amendment recognizing NIST standards
nodes.domains_covered: Security Policy Development; Risk Assessment; Encryption Implementation; Access Control Management; Audit Logging; Incident Response; Security Training; Safe Harbor Assessment; Compliance Monitoring; Breach Investigation
nodes.primary_responsibilities: Develop and implement security policies procedures and technical/physical/administrative safeguards for ePHI protection; conduct regular risk assessments to identify vulnerabilities and threats; oversee implementation of encryption access controls and audit logging; ensure incident response procedures are in place; manage security training and awareness; coordinate with privacy officer; respond to security breaches and incidents; maintain security documentation
nodes.regulatory_scope: Organizational-wide scope within covered entity or business associate
nodes.description: Individual designated by covered entity or business associate responsible for developing implementing and maintaining security policies and procedures for protecting electronic PHI (ePHI) and ensuring compliance with HIPAA Security Rule and HITECH Act security enhancements including risk assessment and encryption requirements
nodes.compliance_obligations: Responsibility for Security Rule compliance; implementation of required technical physical and administrative safeguards; risk assessment and management; encryption and access control requirements; audit logging and monitoring; incident response; security training and documentation; evidence of recognized security practices for Safe Harbor
nodes.examples: Covered Entities; Business Associates; Healthcare Providers
nodes.enforcement_authority: Reports to organization leadership; subject to HHS OCR audit and enforcement authority; accountable for security compliance failures and breaches resulting from inadequate safeguards

nodes.authority_source: HIPAA Compliance requirements (45 CFR Parts 160 and 164); HITECH Act amendments; HIPAA Rules generally
nodes.domains_covered: Compliance Program Development; Monitoring and Auditing; Corrective Action Plans; Training and Awareness; Documentation Management; Regulatory Coordination; Breach Investigation; Risk Assessment
nodes.primary_responsibilities: Oversee implementation and maintenance of all HIPAA and HITECH compliance activities; coordinate between privacy and security officers; establish compliance monitoring procedures and audit protocols; manage corrective action plans when violations are identified; maintain compliance documentation; respond to regulatory audits and investigations; ensure staff training and awareness; report compliance status to leadership
nodes.regulatory_scope: Organizational-wide scope within covered entity or business associate
nodes.description: Individual or department responsible for ensuring covered entity or business associate compliance with all applicable HIPAA Privacy Rule Security Rule Breach Notification Rule and HITECH Act requirements; coordinates compliance efforts across privacy security and other regulatory areas
nodes.compliance_obligations: Responsibility for coordinating all HIPAA and HITECH compliance activities; implementation of compliance monitoring and audit procedures; corrective action plan development and implementation; documentation and reporting; staff training and awareness; response to regulatory investigations and enforcement actions
nodes.examples: Covered Entities; Business Associates; Healthcare Providers
nodes.enforcement_authority: Reports to organization leadership and board; subject to HHS OCR audit and enforcement authority; accountable for compliance failures; required to report compliance status to governing body

nodes.authority_source: HIPAA Audit Standards (45 CFR § 164.308(a)(8) Audit Controls); HITECH Act supporting compliance monitoring requirements
nodes.domains_covered: Compliance Auditing; Gap Assessment; Control Evaluation; Remediation Tracking; Documentation Review; Risk Assessment; Regulatory Readiness Assessment
nodes.primary_responsibilities: Conduct regular internal audits and assessments of Privacy Rule Security Rule and Breach Notification Rule compliance; assess effectiveness of policies procedures and controls; identify compliance gaps and areas for improvement; document audit findings and recommendations; follow up on remediation of identified issues; maintain audit documentation and work papers; provide management with assessment reports
nodes.regulatory_scope: Organizational-wide scope within covered entity or business associate
nodes.description: Individual or team within or contracted by covered entity or business associate responsible for conducting internal audits and assessments of HIPAA and HITECH compliance including privacy security and breach notification procedures
nodes.compliance_obligations: Responsibility for conducting objective audits and assessments of HIPAA and HITECH compliance; documenting findings; recommending improvements; following up on remediation; maintaining audit documentation; providing management with independent assessment of compliance status
nodes.examples: Covered Entities; Business Associates
nodes.enforcement_authority: Reports to organization leadership (often compliance officer or chief financial officer); subject to HHS OCR review during investigations; audit findings used in OCR penalty assessments

nodes.retention_requirements: Retain for minimum 6 years for audit purposes; longer retention may be required for HIPAA documentation; business associate contracts require document retention
nodes.domains_covered: Privacy & Security Protection; Breach Notification; Business Associate Accountability; Encryption Standards; Access Controls; Audit Logging; Incident Response; Risk Assessment; Encryption; Safeguards Implementation
nodes.description: Individually identifiable health information transmitted or maintained in electronic form; includes all health data that can be linked to an individual including patient name medical record number account numbers SSN date of birth and any other identifier
nodes.disposal_requirements: Secure deletion using NIST-approved methods; encryption key destruction; certified destruction procedures; documentation of destruction; no recovery possible after deletion
nodes.minimum_safeguards: Encryption standards; Access control policies; Unique user identification; Role-based access control; Session timeouts; Audit logging; Encryption key management; Incident response procedures; Business associate agreements; Risk assessment
nodes.protection_requirements: Encryption at rest (AES-256) and in transit (TLS 1.2+); access controls with MFA; audit logging (6+ years); regular risk assessment; incident response procedures; safeguard implementation per HIPAA Security Rule; business associate agreements for handling
nodes.applicable_sections: Section 13400 (Definitions); Section 13402 (Breach Notification); Section 13408 (BA Requirements); Section 13417 (Privacy/Security Enhancements)
nodes.compliance_obligations: Implement Privacy Rule restrictions on use and disclosure; Implement Security Rule technical physical and administrative safeguards; Maintain audit logs of all access; Conduct annual risk assessment; Provide privacy notices to individuals; Allow individual access and amendment rights; Report breaches to individuals HHS and media if 500+; Execute business associate agreements; Provide breach notification within 60 days
nodes.examples: Patient medical records; Insurance claims; Prescription information; Lab results; Vital signs; Immunization records; Hospital discharge summaries; Psychiatric evaluations; Genetic information; Substance abuse treatment records; Any record with patient name or unique identifier linked to health data
nodes.enforcement_authority: HHS OCR; State Attorneys General; Department of Justice (criminal); CMS (if EHR incentive program participant)
nodes.handling_restrictions: Restricted access only to authorized personnel with need-to-know; limited uses and disclosures; no disclosure without authorization except as permitted by law or individual consent; data minimization principle; secure transmission
nodes.regulatory_definition: Under HIPAA and HITECH: any health information in electronic format that can identify an individual including patient name medical record number account numbers SSN date of birth and any other identifier
nodes.key_identifiers: Name; Medical record number; Account number; Social Security number; Date of birth; Street address; Zip code; Phone number; Email address; Health plan beneficiary number; Insurance policy number; Employee ID; Employer name; Emergency contact information

nodes.retention_requirements: Retain de-identification documentation for audit trail purposes; typical retention 2-3 years minimum for regulatory purposes; some research use may require longer retention
nodes.domains_covered: Privacy & Security - De-identification; Research and Quality Improvement; Data Minimization; Regulatory Compliance
nodes.description: Health information from which all individual identifiers have been removed under HIPAA de-identification standards; no longer considered Protected Health Information and may be used and disclosed without restriction
nodes.breach_notification_required: No - de-identified data is not subject to HIPAA Breach Notification Rule and does not trigger breach notification obligations
nodes.disposal_requirements: Standard data archival practices; destruction verification may be required for audit documentation; less stringent than EPHI disposal procedures; documentation of de-identification process retention adequate
nodes.minimum_safeguards: De-identification verification documentation; Safe harbor method verification (removal of 18 identifiers or statistical de-identification); Quality assurance procedures for de-identification process; Version control and tracking; Secure storage during de-identification process
nodes.protection_requirements: While not subject to HIPAA restrictions after de-identification some safeguards recommended: general security practices; version control; source tracking; audit trail of de-identification process; verification documentation
nodes.applicable_sections: Section 13400 (Definitions); Section 13402 (Breach Notification - exemption); HIPAA 45 CFR 164.502(b); HIPAA 45 CFR Part 164 Appendix A (safe harbor method)
nodes.compliance_obligations: Verify de-identification meets HIPAA safe harbor or statistical methods; Document de-identification process; Maintain audit trail; Establish reasonable basis that re-identification is not possible; Retain de-identification verification documentation; Conduct periodic quality assurance of de-identification procedures
nodes.examples: Aggregate patient statistics; Research datasets with identifiers removed; Quality improvement data; Public health surveillance data; Clinical trial data after de-identification; Benchmark data for performance comparison; De-identified claims data
nodes.enforcement_authority: HHS OCR (for verification disputes); State Attorneys General (for misrepresentation); Department of Justice (if fraudulent misrepresentation)
nodes.handling_restrictions: No formal restrictions on use and disclosure once properly de-identified; can be used for research quality improvement operations and other purposes without individual consent; reasonable basis to believe re-identification is not possible
nodes.regulatory_definition: Under HIPAA 45 CFR 164.502(b): health information that does not identify an individual and cannot reasonably be used to identify an individual has been de-identified through removal of all 18 specific identifiers listed in HIPAA regulations
nodes.key_identifiers: No individual identifiers present; Aggregate statistics only; Statistical sufficiency maintained; List of 18 identifiers verified as removed; No reasonable basis to re-identify

nodes.retention_requirements: Retain linkage key for duration of research study or project plus 6 years; De-identified data research use may continue after linkage key destruction; Retain audit logs of key access for 6+ years; Retention depends on research protocol and institutional policies
nodes.domains_covered: Privacy & Security Protection; Research Governance; Data Minimization; Breach Notification (if re-identification occurs); Access Control; Encryption; Key Management; Audit Logging
nodes.description: Health information where personal identifiers have been replaced with a random code or pseudonym but linkage key exists that allows re-identification under controlled conditions; considered PHI and requires HIPAA protection even with identifiers replaced
nodes.breach_notification_required: Yes - if linkage key is compromised or breaches occur pseudonymization integrity is violated and breach notification is triggered
nodes.disposal_requirements: Secure destruction of linkage key when no longer needed; Pseudo-anonymized data can be retained longer after key destruction; Method: cryptographic erasure of keys using NIST-approved methods; Certification of key destruction; Documentation of destruction; Residual data testing
nodes.minimum_safeguards: Encryption of data at rest and in transit; Encryption of linkage key; Separate secure storage of linkage key from data; Dual control authentication; Access logging to both data and linkage key; MFA for key access; Regular backup and testing of linkage key recovery; Incident response procedures; Business associate agreements if third party holds key or data
nodes.protection_requirements: Encryption for the data itself (AES-256 at rest TLS 1.2+ in transit); encryption of linkage key; separate secure storage of linkage key from pseudonymized data; access controls to both data and linkage key; dual control authentication for key access; audit logging of linkage key access; incident response procedures for both data and key
nodes.applicable_sections: Section 13400 (Definitions - PHI remains even with pseudonymization); Section 13402 (Breach Notification if re-identification); Section 13408 (BA Requirements if third-party holds data)
nodes.compliance_obligations: Implement same Privacy and Security protections as EPHI for pseudonymized data; Protect linkage key equivalent to encryption keys; Implement dual-control access to linkage key; Maintain separate audit logs for data and key access; Conduct regular security assessments; Incident response plan for potential key compromise; Research institutional review board (IRB) approval; Data use agreements
nodes.examples: Clinical trial participant data; Longitudinal research datasets; Electronic health record data for research use; Biobank specimens linked to health data; Multi-site research projects; Comparative effectiveness research; Post-marketing surveillance data; Registry data
nodes.enforcement_authority: HHS OCR (for compliance with Privacy and Security Rules); State Attorneys General (for privacy violations); Department of Justice (for criminal violations); Institutional Review Boards (IRB) for research governance; Funding agencies (NIH NSF for research compliance)
nodes.handling_restrictions: Restricted access to pseudonymized data limited to authorized research personnel; Access to linkage key limited to essential personnel only; Dual control requirement for key access; No disclosure of linkage key without authorization; Separation of duties between data handlers and key keepers; Regular audit of access patterns; Monitoring for suspicious access patterns
nodes.regulatory_definition: Health information where identifiers have been replaced with a code or other proxy and remains potential to re-identify through linkage key management; retains PHI status for HIPAA purposes because re-identification remains possible
nodes.key_identifiers: Linkage key maintained separately; Code or pseudonym substituted for identifiers; Re-identification possible through key; Access logs document key usage; Dual control enforced for key access; Audit trail of all key-related activities

nodes.retention_requirements: Typical retention for operational data 2-3 years; research aggregate data longer retention as needed for research; audit trail of aggregation process retention 2-3 years minimum; compliance documentation may require longer retention
nodes.domains_covered: Privacy & Security - Aggregation; Quality Improvement; Benchmarking; Research and Analytics; Performance Reporting; Comparative Analysis; Public Health Reporting
nodes.description: Statistical summaries of health information that combine data from multiple individuals; no individual-level data present; summary statistics counts percentages averages across groups
nodes.breach_notification_required: No - properly aggregated data is generally not subject to HIPAA Breach Notification if data cannot be linked back to individuals
nodes.disposal_requirements: Standard archival and destruction procedures for statistical reports; destruction verification not required if no individual identifiers possible; documentation of aggregation methodology and verification retention adequate
nodes.minimum_safeguards: Verification procedures that aggregation meets HIPAA statistical standards; Documentation of aggregation methodology; Quality assurance for aggregate-level accuracy; Version control for statistical reports; Access controls to prevent report modification; Secure storage for confidentiality
nodes.protection_requirements: General security practices for summary statistics; version control; source tracking; aggregate-level access controls; authentication for system access; basic audit logging of report generation
nodes.applicable_sections: Section 13400 (Definitions - analysis of de-identified or aggregated data not restricted); HIPAA 45 CFR 164.502(b) (aggregated data may not constitute PHI)
nodes.compliance_obligations: Verify aggregation meets HIPAA standards and produces results that do not identify individuals; Document aggregation methodology; Implement quality assurance for statistical accuracy; Maintain audit trail of report generation; Consider state laws on statistical data; Implement contractual protections; Regular review of aggregation procedures
nodes.examples: Hospital readmission rates; Infection rates by department; Average length of stay statistics; Medication error rates; Patient satisfaction scores by department; Diagnostic code frequency distributions; Vaccination coverage percentages; Mortality statistics; Performance metrics for hospital accreditation; Benchmark data for comparative analysis
nodes.enforcement_authority: HHS OCR (if improper aggregation creates identifiability); State Attorneys General (state privacy law violations); Funding agencies (research compliance)
nodes.handling_restrictions: No formal HIPAA restrictions on use if properly aggregated; can be used for benchmarking performance comparison research quality improvement and operations; disclosure generally permitted but consider state laws and contractual obligations
nodes.regulatory_definition: Health information presented in summary form aggregated from multiple individuals in a manner that does not identify individuals or permit reasonable identification; generally not subject to HIPAA if properly aggregated but context and identifiability determination required
nodes.key_identifiers: No individual identifiers present; Aggregation meets statistical standards (typically minimum cell size of 5 or 10+); Suppression of small cell counts; Results cannot identify individuals; Sufficient group size to prevent inference

nodes.retention_requirements: Retain genetic information longer than standard EPHI - typically lifetime for medical records; genetic data may remain relevant for family members into future; 6+ years minimum audit logs; genetic test results retained per state law which may exceed HIPAA requirements; research data retention per study protocol
nodes.domains_covered: Privacy & Security Protection - Genetic Data; Genetic Privacy; Family Privacy Protection; Genetic Discrimination Prevention; Informed Consent; Research Governance; Breach Notification - Genetic Data; Access Control - Genetic Data; Genetic Information Segregation
nodes.description: Any information about an individual's genetic composition or the genetic composition of biological relatives; includes genetic test results genetic predispositions family health history and genomic data; heightened sensitivity due to family implications
nodes.breach_notification_required: Yes - within 60 days with specific genetic breach notification procedures; family members who may be affected should be considered for notification; enhanced notification requirements may apply
nodes.disposal_requirements: Enhanced destruction procedures for genetic data; Cryptographic erasure required for genetic data backup; Certified destruction with specific genetic data verification; No recovery possible after destruction; Family privacy considerations in destruction; Documentation of destruction with genetic-specific details
nodes.minimum_safeguards: Enhanced encryption for genetic data specifically; Segregated storage from other PHI where possible; Dual-factor authentication for access; Genetic counselor review and approval for access; Enhanced audit logging with specific genetic data access tracking; Annual risk assessment specific to genetic data; Genetic data-specific security policies; Enhanced incident response procedures; Mandatory genetic testing and re-confirmation if suspected breach
nodes.protection_requirements: Enhanced encryption (AES-256 at rest TLS 1.2+ in transit); more restrictive access controls than standard EPHI; genetic counselor review of access; dual authentication for genetic data access; genetic data segregation from other PHI; enhanced audit logging with specific tracking of genetic data access; incident response procedures specific to genetic breach; family notification protocols
nodes.applicable_sections: Section 13400 (Definitions - genetic data is PHI); Section 13402 (Breach Notification); Section 13417 (Enhanced Privacy/Security protections); State Genetic Privacy Laws; Genetic Information Nondiscrimination Act (GINA); 42 USC 1320d-9
nodes.compliance_obligations: Implement enhanced privacy and security protections beyond standard HIPAA; Obtain explicit informed consent for genetic testing and use; Restrict genetic information use to treatment unless consent obtained for research; Implement genetic-specific access controls; Segregate genetic data from other PHI where feasible; Conduct annual genetic data security assessments; Provide genetic counseling for results interpretation; Family notification protocols for genetic findings; Ensure GINA compliance to prevent genetic discrimination; Monitor for unauthorized access to genetic data; Implement genetic data retention and destruction policies that exceed standard HIPAA timelines
nodes.examples: Genetic test results; DNA sequencing results; Genetic predisposition information; Family health history indicating genetic tests; Carrier status information; Pathogenic variant information; Ethnic origin (genomic); Genomic biomarkers; Genetic risk scores; Whole genome sequencing data; Exome sequencing data
